04085nam a22006015i 9780226580753DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265807537 a10.7208/97802265807532doi  a(DE-B1597)522585  a(OCoLC)1053888212  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aRC339.C4bB395 2019 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a362.209512231 aBaum, Emily, eauthor.14aThe Invention of Madness :bState, Society, and the Insane in Modern China /cEmily Baum. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b10 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies of the Weatherhead East Asian Institute00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Contracting the "Mad Illness" -- t2. The Birth of the Chinese Asylum, 1901-1918 -- t3. The Institutionalization of Madness, 1910s-1920s -- t4. The Psychiatric Entrepreneur, 1920s-1930s -- t5. From Madness to Mental Illness, 1928-1935 -- t6. Mental Hygiene and Political Control, 1928-1937 -- t7. Between the Mad and the Mentally Ill -- tConclusion -- tGlossary of Chinese Terms -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tStudies of the Weatherhead East Asian Institute, Columbia University0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThroughout most of history, in China the insane were kept within the home and treated by healers who claimed no specialized knowledge of their condition. In the first decade of the twentieth century, however, psychiatric ideas and institutions began to influence longstanding beliefs about the proper treatment for the mentally ill. In The Invention of Madness, Emily Baum traces a genealogy of insanity from the turn of the century to the onset of war with Japan in 1937, revealing the complex and convoluted ways in which "madness" was transformed in the Chinese imagination into "mental illness." ​ Focusing on typically marginalized historical actors, including municipal functionaries and the urban poor, The Invention of Madness shifts our attention from the elite desire for modern medical care to the ways in which psychiatric discourses were implemented and redeployed in the midst of everyday life. New meanings and practices of madness, Baum argues, were not just imposed on the Beijing public but continuously invented by a range of people in ways that reflected their own needs and interests. Exhaustively researched and theoretically informed, The Invention of Madness is an innovative contribution to medical history, urban studies, and the social history of twentieth-century China.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aMental health serviceszChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMental illnesszChinaxHistoryy20th century. 4aBeijing. 4aChina. 4aasylum. 4amadness. 4amedicine. 4amental illness. 4apolice. 4apsychiatry. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226580753423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226580753.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles